WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.780 --> 00:00:06.290
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress, in Washington, D.C.

00:00:06.290 --> 00:00:07.930
&gt;&gt; Mary Louise Kelly:
Hello everybody.

00:00:07.930 --> 00:00:09.780
My name is Mary Louise Kelly.

00:00:09.780 --> 00:00:12.580
I am the National Security
Correspondent for NPR.

00:00:12.580 --> 00:00:16.120
I write spy thrillers
and cover the spy beat.

00:00:16.120 --> 00:00:19.630
And I am delighted to be here as
part of the National Book Festival.

00:00:19.630 --> 00:00:21.670
And I have been especially
looking forward

00:00:21.670 --> 00:00:23.250
to the chance to talk to you.

00:00:23.250 --> 00:00:25.390 position:56%
Please welcome Anne-Marie Slaughter.

00:00:25.390 --> 00:00:27.190
&gt;&gt; Anne-Marie Slaughter: Thank you.

00:00:27.190 --> 00:00:30.990
[ Applause ]

00:00:30.990 --> 00:00:34.430
&gt;&gt; So I will introduce
Anne-Marie as President and CEO.

00:00:34.430 --> 00:00:36.160
Of the New America Foundation.

00:00:36.160 --> 00:00:38.710
Which is a think-tank
based here in Washington.

00:00:38.710 --> 00:00:43.750
However, I suspect that
most people in this room.

00:00:43.750 --> 00:00:45.840
Knew you, at least initially,

00:00:45.840 --> 00:00:48.860
because of a little
article that you wrote.

00:00:48.860 --> 00:00:50.340
Which electrified the country,

00:00:50.340 --> 00:00:52.230
I think it's safe to
say, four years ago.

00:00:52.230 --> 00:00:57.380
The article was headlined, "Why
Women Still Can't Have It All."

00:00:57.380 --> 00:01:02.240
It was the cover of <i>The Atlantic</i>
magazine, in the summer of 2012.

00:01:02.240 --> 00:01:04.630
It, overnight, became
the most read article

00:01:04.630 --> 00:01:07.290
in the history of that magazine.

00:01:07.290 --> 00:01:10.480
And you have since expanded on
it and turned it into a book.

00:01:10.480 --> 00:01:12.300
Which is what we are
here to talk about.

00:01:12.300 --> 00:01:13.600
Called <i>Unfinished Business</i>.

00:01:13.600 --> 00:01:14.900
Congratulations.

00:01:14.900 --> 00:01:16.200
&gt;&gt; Anne-Marie Slaughter: Thank you.

00:01:16.200 --> 00:01:17.500
&gt;&gt; Mary Louise Kelly: And welcome.

00:01:17.500 --> 00:01:18.800
[ Applause ]

00:01:18.800 --> 00:01:21.520
So I actually want to
start with that headline.

00:01:21.520 --> 00:01:24.300 position:56%
Because, as I say, I've been looking
forward to this conversation.

00:01:24.300 --> 00:01:28.140
And yesterday, I tweeted, why
women still can't have it all.

00:01:28.140 --> 00:01:29.570
Looking forward to
putting that question

00:01:29.570 --> 00:01:32.570
to Ann-Marie Slaughter
at the book festival.

00:01:32.570 --> 00:01:33.870
And you tweeted back.

00:01:33.870 --> 00:01:36.620
And you said, we've actually
moved past that question.

00:01:36.620 --> 00:01:37.920
And I thought --

00:01:37.920 --> 00:01:39.220
[ Laughter ]

00:01:39.220 --> 00:01:40.520
-- We have?

00:01:40.520 --> 00:01:41.820
How did I miss that?

00:01:41.820 --> 00:01:43.120
[ Laughter ]

00:01:43.120 --> 00:01:44.420
Let me throw that question
to you first.

00:01:44.420 --> 00:01:45.720
Have you figured it all out?

00:01:45.720 --> 00:01:47.020
You've cracked this,
and we can have it all?

00:01:47.020 --> 00:01:49.020
And you're here to tell us how?

00:01:49.020 --> 00:01:50.560
&gt;&gt; Anne-Marie Slaughter:
So, I'm delighted to be

00:01:50.560 --> 00:01:52.450
at the National Book Festival.

00:01:52.450 --> 00:01:56.480
What is better than a day
entirely devoted to books?

00:01:56.480 --> 00:01:59.010
I -- it is -- it's the best.

00:01:59.010 --> 00:02:00.410
[ Applause ]

00:02:00.410 --> 00:02:04.180
And I love the fact that our
conversation started on Twitter.

00:02:04.180 --> 00:02:06.420
And now continues today.

00:02:06.420 --> 00:02:10.210
And so what I meant was.

00:02:10.210 --> 00:02:13.370
One of the things I've learned
since writing that article.

00:02:13.370 --> 00:02:18.320
Is that we really want to move
past the frame of having it all.

00:02:18.320 --> 00:02:22.010
And actually, Rebecca Traister
originally wrote a post.

00:02:22.010 --> 00:02:23.390
After my article came out.

00:02:23.390 --> 00:02:25.310
And taught me things I didn't know.

00:02:25.310 --> 00:02:28.720
Which is that having it all
came from Helen Gurley Brown.

00:02:28.720 --> 00:02:30.020
The editor of <i>Cosmo</i>.

00:02:30.020 --> 00:02:35.020
I think she had a different idea
of what having it all means.

00:02:35.020 --> 00:02:40.250
But, more broadly, it
makes women sound selfish.

00:02:40.250 --> 00:02:43.300
Right? We're living in
a country where millions

00:02:43.300 --> 00:02:46.770 position:56%
of people are trying to have enough.

00:02:46.770 --> 00:02:49.320
To simply get by.

00:02:49.320 --> 00:02:52.380
And to pose it as 'can
I have it all?'

00:02:52.380 --> 00:02:54.570
Even though you can say that's
part of the American DNA.

00:02:54.570 --> 00:02:59.280 position:56%
I think, starts the whole
conversation off in the wrong place.

00:02:59.280 --> 00:03:02.050
So I no longer use the phrase.

00:03:02.050 --> 00:03:04.960
I talk about equality
between men and women.

00:03:04.960 --> 00:03:06.430
Or gender equality.

00:03:06.430 --> 00:03:10.000
And I talk about how can all of us.

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:12.000 position:56%
And that means men as well as women.

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:15.340
And I am so thrilled to see
so many men in this audience.

00:03:15.340 --> 00:03:19.220
How can men and women work?

00:03:19.220 --> 00:03:23.030
Live in a way that
they can work and care

00:03:23.030 --> 00:03:25.050
for their loved ones
at the same time?

00:03:25.050 --> 00:03:27.100
You notice, I also
didn't use balance.

00:03:27.100 --> 00:03:29.870
How can we fit those
two things together?

00:03:29.870 --> 00:03:31.170
That's the question.

00:03:31.170 --> 00:03:32.470
&gt;&gt; Mary Louise Kelly: Okay.

00:03:32.470 --> 00:03:33.770
And I want to hear some of
your specific thoughts on that.

00:03:33.770 --> 00:03:35.070
But before we get ahead
of ourselves.

00:03:35.070 --> 00:03:37.030 position:56%
Let me let you just tell your story.

00:03:37.030 --> 00:03:40.090
Of how you came to write that
article and then the book.

00:03:40.090 --> 00:03:43.120
You -- I wonder if you can
take us back to that moment?

00:03:43.120 --> 00:03:45.670
Where you had finally
gotten the dream job.

00:03:45.670 --> 00:03:50.270
You're this high-power position
at the State Department.

00:03:50.270 --> 00:03:52.210
And realized it wasn't
working [inaudible].

00:03:52.210 --> 00:03:55.670
It wasn't working -- you weren't
able to do the job you needed to do

00:03:55.670 --> 00:03:56.970
at home with your family.

00:03:56.970 --> 00:03:58.270
What happened?

00:03:58.270 --> 00:04:00.320
Tell us where you were and
what was going on in your life.

00:04:00.320 --> 00:04:01.940
&gt;&gt; Anne-Marie Slaughter: So
the first thing you say is yes.

00:04:01.940 --> 00:04:05.230
This was absolutely a dream job.

00:04:05.230 --> 00:04:07.880
To be the first woman
director of policy planning.

00:04:07.880 --> 00:04:10.810
It's the big think-job
in the State Department.

00:04:10.810 --> 00:04:13.910
Secretary Clinton wanted
to put a woman in that job.

00:04:13.910 --> 00:04:17.440
To show that, you know, we
could do the big thinking too.

00:04:17.440 --> 00:04:20.260
And it, you know, I was there
in her early morning meeting.

00:04:20.260 --> 00:04:22.450
Every morning, at 8:45.

00:04:22.450 --> 00:04:24.360
That's very heady.

00:04:24.360 --> 00:04:25.660
And I loved it.

00:04:25.660 --> 00:04:27.230
I left my family in Princeton.

00:04:27.230 --> 00:04:30.410
There was no way to move my
husband and sons to Washington.

00:04:30.410 --> 00:04:33.540 position:56%
I mean, they were at that point in
middle school and elementary school.

00:04:33.540 --> 00:04:35.490
My husband teaches in Princeton.

00:04:35.490 --> 00:04:37.010
We would have uprooted them.

00:04:37.010 --> 00:04:38.410
My husband would've had to commute.

00:04:38.410 --> 00:04:39.930
That was never an option.

00:04:39.930 --> 00:04:42.590
In fact, my sons didn't
want me to leave.

00:04:42.590 --> 00:04:45.260
But once I said, well, how
about moving to Washington?

00:04:45.260 --> 00:04:46.640
It was, "Bye, mom."

00:04:46.640 --> 00:04:48.210
You know, it's like, no.

00:04:48.210 --> 00:04:49.510
They were not moving.

00:04:49.510 --> 00:04:50.810
So I --

00:04:50.810 --> 00:04:52.110
&gt;&gt; Mary Louise Kelly: So
you're doing the train commute?

00:04:52.110 --> 00:04:53.410
&gt;&gt; Anne-Marie Slaughter:
So I would leave.

00:04:53.410 --> 00:04:54.710
I would literally leave the
house at 5 A.M. every morning.

00:04:54.710 --> 00:04:56.530
Feeling like kind of
a thief in the night.

00:04:56.530 --> 00:04:58.040
All three -- got boys are sleeping.

00:04:58.040 --> 00:04:59.340
My husband and my sons.

00:04:59.340 --> 00:05:00.640
And I would come down here.

00:05:00.640 --> 00:05:02.070
Make it in time for
the early meeting.

00:05:02.070 --> 00:05:03.660
And go back late on Friday.

00:05:03.660 --> 00:05:05.570
So it meant I had two days a week.

00:05:05.570 --> 00:05:06.870
And, I mean, look.

00:05:06.870 --> 00:05:10.220
People, many people don't
see their families enough.

00:05:10.220 --> 00:05:12.710
But it was, it was hard.

00:05:12.710 --> 00:05:14.270
But it was doable.

00:05:14.270 --> 00:05:16.810
My husband stepped up
and was the lead parent.

00:05:16.810 --> 00:05:19.560
And then, as I wrote,
my elder son was,

00:05:19.560 --> 00:05:22.390
I think, a not unusual teenager.

00:05:22.390 --> 00:05:23.860
I mean, it's not that he --

00:05:23.860 --> 00:05:25.160
&gt;&gt; Mary Louise Kelly:
Which is to say, what?

00:05:25.160 --> 00:05:26.460 position:56%
A complete nightmare at [inaudible]?

00:05:26.460 --> 00:05:27.760
&gt;&gt; Anne-Marie Slaughter:
More or less.

00:05:27.760 --> 00:05:29.060
Yeah.

00:05:29.060 --> 00:05:30.360
&gt;&gt; Mary Louise Kelly: Having
a new teenager in our house.

00:05:30.360 --> 00:05:31.660
I'll back that up.

00:05:31.660 --> 00:05:32.960
&gt;&gt; Anne-Marie Slaughter: Yeah,
so then he turned into, you know.

00:05:32.960 --> 00:05:35.040
Kind of, you come downstairs
and say "Good morning."

00:05:35.040 --> 00:05:36.340
And he'd take your head off.

00:05:36.340 --> 00:05:38.250
And you'd say, "Excuse
me for living."

00:05:38.250 --> 00:05:42.060
And he would -- but he
was making bad choices.

00:05:42.060 --> 00:05:44.800
And indeed, you know,
I didn't expect that.

00:05:44.800 --> 00:05:46.940
He was with the wrong crowd.

00:05:46.940 --> 00:05:48.380
Many parents know this.

00:05:48.380 --> 00:05:50.330
He was tuning out at school.

00:05:50.330 --> 00:05:53.380
He started getting into
trouble with the local police.

00:05:53.380 --> 00:05:54.680
Little stuff.

00:05:54.680 --> 00:05:57.930
But enough that, you
know, I'd get a call.

00:05:57.930 --> 00:06:00.890
And Andy would say, you
know, "He's been suspended."

00:06:00.890 --> 00:06:02.500
And I'd be, "Suspended?"

00:06:02.500 --> 00:06:05.900
You know, it was -- I
was not prepared for it.

00:06:05.900 --> 00:06:09.430
And it got to the point
that I was literally asking.

00:06:09.430 --> 00:06:10.820
What am I doing here?

00:06:10.820 --> 00:06:12.680
You know, why am I here?

00:06:12.680 --> 00:06:16.750
When my son so clearly
needs me and his father.

00:06:16.750 --> 00:06:18.670
It wasn't like I was
going to go save the day.

00:06:18.670 --> 00:06:21.160
It was, we needed both
hands on deck.

00:06:21.160 --> 00:06:23.240
And that really just starting

00:06:23.240 --> 00:06:26.300
to change the way I'd
always thought about this.

00:06:26.300 --> 00:06:28.510
I had always said to younger women.

00:06:28.510 --> 00:06:29.880
Of course you can do it.

00:06:29.880 --> 00:06:31.910
You just have to want
to want it enough.

00:06:31.910 --> 00:06:33.210
And I believed that.

00:06:33.210 --> 00:06:34.980
And I knew I had a
lot of advantages.

00:06:34.980 --> 00:06:36.500
A flexible job and money.

00:06:36.500 --> 00:06:37.800
I knew that.

00:06:37.800 --> 00:06:39.540
But I still really
thought, you can do it.

00:06:39.540 --> 00:06:43.220
And when this happened, I
suddenly realized, wait a minute.

00:06:43.220 --> 00:06:45.420
All these other women
who had a divorce.

00:06:45.420 --> 00:06:46.940
Or a child with special needs.

00:06:46.940 --> 00:06:48.240
Or had to move.

00:06:48.240 --> 00:06:50.680
Or don't have the advantages I do.

00:06:50.680 --> 00:06:53.730 position:56%
It's not that they want to drop out.

00:06:53.730 --> 00:06:57.900
They're simply choosing
the people they love.

00:06:57.900 --> 00:07:00.260 position:56%
Over the work they may equally love.

00:07:00.260 --> 00:07:04.890
But that's something we
should admire and celebrate.

00:07:04.890 --> 00:07:10.640
Not accuse them of having
failed some, you know, idea.

00:07:10.640 --> 00:07:12.410
That they're supposed
to be able to do it all.

00:07:12.410 --> 00:07:14.150
And the other thing was.

00:07:14.150 --> 00:07:17.650
There's a huge number of things
we could do in our society.

00:07:17.650 --> 00:07:20.940
To make it a lot easier
for women, as well as men.

00:07:20.940 --> 00:07:22.800
So that's why I wrote the article.

00:07:22.800 --> 00:07:26.650 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Mary Louise Kelly: So let me walk
you through some of the strategies.

00:07:26.650 --> 00:07:27.950
Because I think we're all
sitting here thinking.

00:07:27.950 --> 00:07:30.170
Okay, so how do we --
it's not have it all.

00:07:30.170 --> 00:07:31.750
That's not the way we
should be framing the goal.

00:07:31.750 --> 00:07:34.370
How do we -- how do we try
to have the work we love?

00:07:34.370 --> 00:07:36.510
And take care of the family
that we love at the same time?

00:07:36.510 --> 00:07:38.830 position:56%
One of the things that intrigued me.

00:07:38.830 --> 00:07:41.430
That you propose, is
interval training.

00:07:41.430 --> 00:07:42.730
&gt;&gt; Anne-Marie Slaughter: Yeah.

00:07:42.730 --> 00:07:44.030
&gt;&gt; Mary Louise Kelly:
Explain what you mean by that.

00:07:44.030 --> 00:07:45.330
&gt;&gt; Anne-Marie Slaughter:
So in the book --

00:07:45.330 --> 00:07:46.630
&gt;&gt; Mary Louise Kelly: Because
I'm visioning a treadmill.

00:07:46.630 --> 00:07:48.030
And that's just not what it is.

00:07:48.030 --> 00:07:52.040
&gt;&gt; Anne-Marie Slaughter: So one of
the core reasons this is so hard.

00:07:52.040 --> 00:07:57.720
Is that we still have a 1950s
idea of what a career looks like.

00:07:57.720 --> 00:07:59.030
You come out of school.

00:07:59.030 --> 00:08:00.840
You plunge into your career.

00:08:00.840 --> 00:08:03.020
You start climbing this ladder.

00:08:03.020 --> 00:08:06.590
In your 30s and 40s, or
in my case, 40s and 50s.

00:08:06.590 --> 00:08:08.560
When you are having children.

00:08:08.560 --> 00:08:11.550
When, typically, when most
of us are having children.

00:08:11.550 --> 00:08:14.480
That's right at the heart of
the hard part of the ladder.

00:08:14.480 --> 00:08:16.770
And you're soaring up,
and you reach your peak.

00:08:16.770 --> 00:08:19.180
Sometime in your 50s
or your early 60s.

00:08:19.180 --> 00:08:22.680 position:56%
You retire at 65, and you die at 75.

00:08:22.680 --> 00:08:25.610
That isn't our lives.

00:08:25.610 --> 00:08:27.690
That's just not our lives.

00:08:27.690 --> 00:08:31.360
Girls today have a
life expectancy of 86.

00:08:31.360 --> 00:08:34.890
Which means a large number of
people are expected to live to 100.

00:08:34.890 --> 00:08:38.050
And you can read plenty of things
on the cover of <i>TIME</i> magazine.

00:08:38.050 --> 00:08:39.680
That says we're going
to live to 120.

00:08:39.680 --> 00:08:41.900
And I don't know what
we're going to do then.

00:08:41.900 --> 00:08:44.730
But there's plenty of time.

00:08:44.730 --> 00:08:49.300
If Hillary Clinton wins, she'll
be 70 when she becomes president.

00:08:49.300 --> 00:08:52.540
And she didn't start
her political career

00:08:52.540 --> 00:08:54.830 position:56%
until after Chelsea went to college.

00:08:54.830 --> 00:08:57.170
You know, she was a lawyer
and she did lots of things.

00:08:57.170 --> 00:08:59.290
But she started --
she ran for Senate.

00:08:59.290 --> 00:09:00.590
She ran for president.

00:09:00.590 --> 00:09:01.890
She became secretary of state.

00:09:01.890 --> 00:09:03.190
She ran for president again.

00:09:03.190 --> 00:09:04.700
All after her daughter
went to college.

00:09:04.700 --> 00:09:07.780
So interval training
is the idea that all

00:09:07.780 --> 00:09:09.310 position:56%
of us would think about our careers.

00:09:09.310 --> 00:09:11.380
As periods where we go hard.

00:09:11.380 --> 00:09:12.680
Come out of school.

00:09:12.680 --> 00:09:13.980
You're young.

00:09:13.980 --> 00:09:15.280
When I was young, I pulled
plenty of all-nighters.

00:09:15.280 --> 00:09:16.580
You know, I could travel.

00:09:16.580 --> 00:09:17.880
I could do all that.

00:09:17.880 --> 00:09:19.180
I didn't have a house or a husband.

00:09:19.180 --> 00:09:21.640
Or, you know, I was free.

00:09:21.640 --> 00:09:23.840
You go hard and then you slow down.

00:09:23.840 --> 00:09:27.400
This is how athletes get
into peak performance.

00:09:27.400 --> 00:09:28.700
Training, right?

00:09:28.700 --> 00:09:30.000
You think about on a Stairmaster.

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:31.990
You go hard and you slow down.

00:09:31.990 --> 00:09:35.670
And women and men should be
able to think of their careers.

00:09:35.670 --> 00:09:38.160
In terms of multiple intervals.

00:09:38.160 --> 00:09:40.290
So that they're going
to work longer.

00:09:40.290 --> 00:09:43.160
But they're also going to have
time for the people they love.

00:09:43.160 --> 00:09:45.810
Because your kids are
only young once.

00:09:45.810 --> 00:09:50.380
And your parents are only
aging and needing you, once.

00:09:50.380 --> 00:09:52.250
Or a spouse who is ill.

00:09:52.250 --> 00:09:53.950
Or anybody else in your family.

00:09:53.950 --> 00:09:57.680
And in -- really, there's no
reason there isn't time for both.

00:09:57.680 --> 00:10:00.890
Except for we have this
very artificial idea

00:10:00.890 --> 00:10:02.890
of how you have to work.

00:10:02.890 --> 00:10:04.200
&gt;&gt; Mary Louise Kelly:
So where are you

00:10:04.200 --> 00:10:05.590 position:56%
