00:31:24.950 --> 00:31:26.330
There are things like,

00:31:26.330 --> 00:31:29.830
you can mandate not
discriminating against people.

00:31:29.830 --> 00:31:32.750
On the basis of part-time
work or flexible work.

00:31:32.750 --> 00:31:35.240
That one is harder to legislate.

00:31:35.240 --> 00:31:37.630
But there are ways that
you can encourage it.

00:31:37.630 --> 00:31:38.930
And provide incentives.

00:31:38.930 --> 00:31:40.230
And the first two.

00:31:40.230 --> 00:31:43.640
On paid family leave, I
think business is going

00:31:43.640 --> 00:31:44.960
to want federal standards.

00:31:44.960 --> 00:31:46.840
Because right now,
we have four states.

00:31:46.840 --> 00:31:50.110
Including New York and California.

00:31:50.110 --> 00:31:52.800
So two huge states that
have paid family leave.

00:31:52.800 --> 00:31:54.260
And a bunch of cities.

00:31:54.260 --> 00:31:56.200
That means you're going to
have a patchwork, right?

00:31:56.200 --> 00:31:59.750 position:56%
It's going to be very unpredictable,
which city or state you're in.

00:31:59.750 --> 00:32:03.270
And gradually, then, business
would prefer one uniform standard.

00:32:03.270 --> 00:32:04.770
So that one, definitely.

00:32:04.770 --> 00:32:07.940
Childcare, you know,
President Nixon vetoed a bill.

00:32:07.940 --> 00:32:10.020
That had been passed by
both houses of Congress.

00:32:10.020 --> 00:32:13.200
For universal childcare, in 1971.

00:32:13.200 --> 00:32:14.670
It'd be great to get back there.

00:32:14.670 --> 00:32:16.770
But I'd settle for
lots of incentives.

00:32:16.770 --> 00:32:20.050
And other things that
encourage both on-site childcare

00:32:20.050 --> 00:32:21.740
and community care.

00:32:21.740 --> 00:32:23.040
&gt;&gt; Mary Louise Kelly:
Okay, thank you.

00:32:23.040 --> 00:32:24.340
Question right here.

00:32:24.340 --> 00:32:25.640
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:32:25.640 --> 00:32:28.910
My question is going to be about
transition in interval training.

00:32:28.910 --> 00:32:32.610
And my context is, I'm a
military family member.

00:32:32.610 --> 00:32:33.910
So my husband is active duty.

00:32:33.910 --> 00:32:36.010
He deployed, I ramp it up.

00:32:36.010 --> 00:32:37.920
I am also in the military,
as a reservist.

00:32:37.920 --> 00:32:39.230
And I have a civilian career.

00:32:39.230 --> 00:32:40.820
My turn to deploy is coming.

00:32:40.820 --> 00:32:42.120
&gt;&gt; Anne-Marie Slaughter: Yeah.

00:32:42.120 --> 00:32:43.420
&gt;&gt; So how, when you're
not changing jobs?

00:32:43.420 --> 00:32:46.170
But you are going to
have different abilities.

00:32:46.170 --> 00:32:49.910
In how much time you can devote
to that, and not everything else.

00:32:49.910 --> 00:32:51.210
&gt;&gt; Anne-Marie Slaughter: Yep.

00:32:51.210 --> 00:32:52.670
&gt;&gt; Can you tell us, what have
your best practices been?

00:32:52.670 --> 00:32:54.530
As you've gone through
some of those intervals?

00:32:54.530 --> 00:32:55.830
How did you transition?

00:32:55.830 --> 00:32:57.130 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Anne-Marie Slaughter: Absolutely.

00:32:57.130 --> 00:32:58.430
So thank you.

00:32:58.430 --> 00:32:59.730 position:56%
And first of all, I should just say.

00:32:59.730 --> 00:33:02.550
When I did feel like I
wasn't ever seeing my family.

00:33:02.550 --> 00:33:03.850
And this was hard.

00:33:03.850 --> 00:33:05.360
I would think to myself, you know.

00:33:05.360 --> 00:33:08.140
Our military deploy
for a year at a time.

00:33:08.140 --> 00:33:10.920
And I'm seeing my children
every sixth day.

00:33:10.920 --> 00:33:13.410
They're seeing -- they're not
seeing their family for a year.

00:33:13.410 --> 00:33:14.820
So I want to start by thanking you.

00:33:14.820 --> 00:33:18.510
For your service and
your husband's service.

00:33:18.510 --> 00:33:23.880
[ Applause ]

00:33:23.880 --> 00:33:26.370
To your question, this
is really important.

00:33:26.370 --> 00:33:28.640
I mean, what we really
do need to do.

00:33:28.640 --> 00:33:31.000
Is change employer attitudes.

00:33:31.000 --> 00:33:35.610
So that when they see,
you know, a part-time job.

00:33:35.610 --> 00:33:37.940
Even no job for a while.

00:33:37.940 --> 00:33:40.970
They don't think, oh, I'm not
going to hire this person.

00:33:40.970 --> 00:33:44.730
I'm going to hire the person that
has that sterling 1950s resume.

00:33:44.730 --> 00:33:46.200
Where it just goes straight up.

00:33:46.200 --> 00:33:48.960
That's the most important
thing we can do.

00:33:48.960 --> 00:33:52.960
But beyond that, you do
need -- I say in the book.

00:33:52.960 --> 00:33:55.110
Don't drop out, defer.

00:33:55.110 --> 00:33:57.770
Right? So defer the big job.

00:33:57.770 --> 00:33:59.860
But keep your skills in.

00:33:59.860 --> 00:34:01.920
Keep your contacts ready.

00:34:01.920 --> 00:34:04.340
Think about things that, you know,

00:34:04.340 --> 00:34:07.030
let's say you need
to learn fundraising.

00:34:07.030 --> 00:34:08.800
Or you need to learn
public speaking.

00:34:08.800 --> 00:34:11.430
Or having something written
with your name on it.

00:34:11.430 --> 00:34:13.580
Would help your career
down the line.

00:34:13.580 --> 00:34:16.290
Use that time to do those things.

00:34:16.290 --> 00:34:18.180
That's also a better story.

00:34:18.180 --> 00:34:20.200
So you can say, yes, you know.

00:34:20.200 --> 00:34:22.440
It was my turn to be lead parent.

00:34:22.440 --> 00:34:24.370
During that time, I wrote this.

00:34:24.370 --> 00:34:27.810
Or I took on a new set of
experiences through volunteering.

00:34:27.810 --> 00:34:31.420
That, I say, think about
your career as a portfolio

00:34:31.420 --> 00:34:33.000
of skills and experiences.

00:34:33.000 --> 00:34:37.710
And figure out where you can add,
even as you're being lead parent.

00:34:37.710 --> 00:34:39.010
&gt;&gt; Mary Louise Kelly:
That's great advice.

00:34:39.010 --> 00:34:40.500
Question here.

00:34:40.500 --> 00:34:41.800
&gt;&gt; Hi, I'm Phil.

00:34:41.800 --> 00:34:43.100
I'm a generic guy.

00:34:43.100 --> 00:34:44.510
[ Laughter ]

00:34:44.510 --> 00:34:45.810
&gt;&gt; Mary Louise Kelly: Welcome.

00:34:45.810 --> 00:34:47.750
&gt;&gt; You're clearly very successful.

00:34:47.750 --> 00:34:50.230
And you talk about success,
and success is good.

00:34:50.230 --> 00:34:52.700
I think we all want
to be successful.

00:34:52.700 --> 00:34:56.240
But I think a big part of
work-life balance is failure.

00:34:56.240 --> 00:34:59.960
It's dealing with your inability to
work as hard as you want at work.

00:34:59.960 --> 00:35:01.260
Make a project go.

00:35:01.260 --> 00:35:03.710
Being absent from your kids
soccer game, etcetera, etcetera.

00:35:03.710 --> 00:35:07.320
Can you tell us about
a time when you failed?

00:35:07.320 --> 00:35:08.620
Seriously failed.

00:35:08.620 --> 00:35:11.210
Maybe a time when you and your
husband came close to divorce.

00:35:11.210 --> 00:35:13.730
Because you couldn't
balance your life and work.

00:35:13.730 --> 00:35:17.110
So that we have some perspective
on what it's really like.

00:35:17.110 --> 00:35:18.820
To really struggle.

00:35:18.820 --> 00:35:20.120
Thank you.

00:35:20.120 --> 00:35:21.420
&gt;&gt; Anne-Marie Slaughter: Okay.

00:35:21.420 --> 00:35:22.720
So I will thank you
for the question.

00:35:22.720 --> 00:35:24.960
It's an important one.

00:35:24.960 --> 00:35:29.610
And I will say two things.

00:35:29.610 --> 00:35:31.660
So one, and I wrote about this.

00:35:31.660 --> 00:35:35.760
When my son was in first
grade -- my elder son.

00:35:35.760 --> 00:35:38.070
He was asked to draw his family.

00:35:38.070 --> 00:35:40.120
And he drew me as a laptop.

00:35:40.120 --> 00:35:42.220
[ Laughter ]

00:35:42.220 --> 00:35:44.340
Not a person typing at a laptop.

00:35:44.340 --> 00:35:45.850
There was no person in the picture.

00:35:45.850 --> 00:35:47.610
There was just a laptop.

00:35:47.610 --> 00:35:48.910
&gt;&gt; Mary Louise Kelly: Ow!

00:35:48.910 --> 00:35:50.210
&gt;&gt; Anne-Marie Slaughter:
That was not a good moment.

00:35:50.210 --> 00:35:52.100
Right? That he drew
his father cooking.

00:35:52.100 --> 00:35:54.210
Right? His father was
there, I wasn't.

00:35:54.210 --> 00:35:56.720
I was just become Dean of
the Woodrow Wilson School.

00:35:56.720 --> 00:35:59.080
And clearly, I was absent.

00:35:59.080 --> 00:36:02.980
So that was not a good moment.

00:36:02.980 --> 00:36:08.390
And yes, I could write an entire
book on inter-spousal negotiation.

00:36:08.390 --> 00:36:11.580
Most of our conversation
consisted of.

00:36:11.580 --> 00:36:13.340
You didn't give me credit for this.

00:36:13.340 --> 00:36:14.820
I did this, you did this.

00:36:14.820 --> 00:36:18.310
We tried every system
under the sun to divide it.

00:36:18.310 --> 00:36:20.650
You know, hours on
the refrigerators.

00:36:20.650 --> 00:36:22.680
Computer apps, you name it.

00:36:22.680 --> 00:36:25.800
Because we were constantly
pulling and tugging.

00:36:25.800 --> 00:36:29.130
And, you know, there are
those games we missed.

00:36:29.130 --> 00:36:34.590
And I don't think my elder son spun
out because I went to Washington.

00:36:34.590 --> 00:36:36.380
But I don't think it helped.

00:36:36.380 --> 00:36:39.520
I think he was trying
really hard to be mature.

00:36:39.520 --> 00:36:40.820
He was 12.

00:36:40.820 --> 00:36:42.940
He knew this was an
important job for me.

00:36:42.940 --> 00:36:44.970
But he had also just
started middle school.

00:36:44.970 --> 00:36:46.640
And I think he felt abandoned.

00:36:46.640 --> 00:36:49.310
And knew he couldn't express that.

00:36:49.310 --> 00:36:51.190
So no question.

00:36:51.190 --> 00:36:54.520
And I'll just conclude that
by saying, at one point.

00:36:54.520 --> 00:36:56.750
My husband and I had
been having a discussion.

00:36:56.750 --> 00:37:00.830
That you might call a fight,
if you were so inclined.

00:37:00.830 --> 00:37:06.020
And my older son came in and
said -- this was a while back.

00:37:06.020 --> 00:37:07.320
And he said, you know, "Mom.

00:37:07.320 --> 00:37:10.650
Are you and dad going to
divorce when we go to college?"

00:37:10.650 --> 00:37:13.110
And I said, "Sweetheart,
when you go to college.

00:37:13.110 --> 00:37:15.070
We won't have anything
to fight about."

00:37:15.070 --> 00:37:17.130
[ Laughter ]

00:37:17.130 --> 00:37:18.430
And that's true.

00:37:18.430 --> 00:37:19.730
So, absolutely.

00:37:19.730 --> 00:37:21.570
But we are -- I mean, all of us.

00:37:21.570 --> 00:37:22.870
This is hard.

00:37:22.870 --> 00:37:24.170
That's part of my point.

00:37:24.170 --> 00:37:25.470
It is hard.

00:37:25.470 --> 00:37:27.040
And if you have anything else.

00:37:27.040 --> 00:37:30.710
Again, a job away, a child
with special needs, a divorce.

00:37:30.710 --> 00:37:33.100
Anything else can tip that.

00:37:33.100 --> 00:37:34.810 position:56%
So then I talk about it in the book.

00:37:34.810 --> 00:37:37.240
The tipping point, where suddenly,
you just can't do it anymore.

00:37:37.240 --> 00:37:38.540
And you've got to change jobs.

00:37:38.540 --> 00:37:41.890
Or you have to, you
know, somehow adjust.

00:37:41.890 --> 00:37:45.650
So that you can respond to
the needs of the moment.

00:37:45.650 --> 00:37:47.050
&gt;&gt; Mary Louise Kelly: Thank you.

00:37:47.050 --> 00:37:48.350
Question here.

00:37:48.350 --> 00:37:49.650
Yes, sir.

00:37:49.650 --> 00:37:52.880
&gt;&gt; I'm wondering what
advice you would give?

00:37:52.880 --> 00:37:57.160
Or what you would say to
a single, working mom.

00:37:57.160 --> 00:38:01.800
Who's going to be vacuuming
this room tonight.

00:38:01.800 --> 00:38:05.750
Or who's working in security
for this building right now.

00:38:05.750 --> 00:38:09.440
Or who's signing up at front.

00:38:09.440 --> 00:38:13.600
&gt;&gt; Anne-Marie Slaughter: So I
would say, that in my article.

00:38:13.600 --> 00:38:15.960
I had nothing to say to her.

00:38:15.960 --> 00:38:18.060
Because I wrote that
article from the position

00:38:18.060 --> 00:38:19.360
of privilege that I was in.

00:38:19.360 --> 00:38:20.660
I knew it.

00:38:20.660 --> 00:38:22.020
I was writing for <i>The Atlantic</i>.

00:38:22.020 --> 00:38:24.370
So I knew what my readership
looked like.

00:38:24.370 --> 00:38:27.840
But I would say, I also
thought about gender issues.

00:38:27.840 --> 00:38:32.690 position:56%
Almost entirely in terms of the fact
there were too few women at the top.

00:38:32.690 --> 00:38:36.640
And that what we needed to do
was to get more women at the top.

00:38:36.640 --> 00:38:38.150
Four years later.

00:38:38.150 --> 00:38:42.370
After three years reading,
writing, wrestling with issues.

00:38:42.370 --> 00:38:45.000
I think, yep, there are
too few women at the top.

00:38:45.000 --> 00:38:47.940
And there are too many
at the bottom.

00:38:47.940 --> 00:38:49.970
The poorest people in our society.

00:38:49.970 --> 00:38:52.550
The poorest people are
those single mothers.

00:38:52.550 --> 00:38:55.940
And two-thirds of minimum
wage workers, shift workers,

00:38:55.940 --> 00:38:58.180
and part-time workers, are women.

00:38:58.180 --> 00:39:01.060
So the reason I focus on care.

00:39:01.060 --> 00:39:05.420
Is because I think the -- I buy
my way out of care problems.

00:39:05.420 --> 00:39:08.020
That mother you're
describing, can't.

00:39:08.020 --> 00:39:10.490
And so things like
paid family leave.

00:39:10.490 --> 00:39:13.580
She can lose her job
when her child is sick.

00:39:13.580 --> 00:39:17.370
That's -- a society that
says you have to choose.

00:39:17.370 --> 00:39:21.280
Between staying home with
the child, and your job.

00:39:21.280 --> 00:39:23.250
Is an immoral society.

00:39:23.250 --> 00:39:25.510
So I'm focused on those issues.

00:39:25.510 --> 00:39:29.220
[ Applause ]

00:39:29.220 --> 00:39:31.800
So thanks for the question.

00:39:31.800 --> 00:39:33.100
&gt;&gt; Mary Louise Kelly: Thank you.

00:39:33.100 --> 00:39:34.400
Right here.

00:39:34.400 --> 00:39:35.700
&gt;&gt; Hi. My name is Caroline.

00:39:35.700 --> 00:39:37.580
I graduated from college
two years ago.

00:39:37.580 --> 00:39:40.380
And I was interested
in what you said

00:39:40.380 --> 00:39:43.590
about the few years
right after you graduate.

00:39:43.590 --> 00:39:45.490
Those being really important years

00:39:45.490 --> 00:39:48.510
to just totally be
all in on your career.

00:39:48.510 --> 00:39:53.050
And what I have found with my
friends, since we graduated.

00:39:53.050 --> 00:39:57.490
And since we lost this incredible
community that we had at school.

00:39:57.490 --> 00:40:00.520
People really clung
to relationships.

00:40:00.520 --> 00:40:05.460 position:56%
My friends really clung to
boyfriends, or guys they'd just met.

00:40:05.460 --> 00:40:07.350
Or partners they'd just met.

00:40:07.350 --> 00:40:13.670
Because they missed that
feeling of community.

00:40:13.670 --> 00:40:17.610
And my question for
you is, you know.

00:40:17.610 --> 00:40:21.280
As we think about how much we
want to value our relationships.

00:40:21.280 --> 00:40:23.700
This early on in our career.

00:40:23.700 --> 00:40:25.210
What's your advice?

00:40:25.210 --> 00:40:30.510
Do you think that it is
crucial to have those years?

00:40:30.510 --> 00:40:34.370
Where you don't think about a
relationship at all, this early?

00:40:34.370 --> 00:40:35.670
&gt;&gt; Anne-Marie Slaughter: That --

00:40:35.670 --> 00:40:37.330
I don't think I've ever
been asked that question.

00:40:37.330 --> 00:40:38.990
And it's an important one.

00:40:38.990 --> 00:40:40.800
I mean, after I wrote my article.

00:40:40.800 --> 00:40:43.650
A young Princeton graduate
wrote to me.

00:40:43.650 --> 00:40:46.620
And said she was going
to leave her job

00:40:46.620 --> 00:40:49.170
to follow her boyfriend
across the country.

00:40:49.170 --> 00:40:51.830 position:56%
And that everybody was disapproving.

00:40:51.830 --> 00:40:54.650
And she said, ironically,
had she been leaving her job

00:40:54.650 --> 00:40:57.180
to follow her girlfriend
across the country.

00:40:57.180 --> 00:40:59.900 position:56%
Probably, it would have been better.

00:40:59.900 --> 00:41:02.830
But her larger point
was, wait just a minute.

00:41:02.830 --> 00:41:05.850
Why is it that Princeton
teaches me I should follow my

00:41:05.850 --> 00:41:07.460
career everywhere?

00:41:07.460 --> 00:41:09.340
And not invest in relationships?

00:41:09.340 --> 00:41:13.620
And I would say, again, that's
been part of my journey.

00:41:13.620 --> 00:41:16.490
The theme of this entire
book festival is journeys.

00:41:16.490 --> 00:41:22.140
And I would say, I now think that
investing in those relationships.

00:41:22.140 --> 00:41:24.090
And I think that is the
work of a lead parent.

00:41:24.090 --> 00:41:27.950
My mother was a homemaker,
was investing in her family.

00:41:27.950 --> 00:41:29.490
Is critically important.

00:41:29.490 --> 00:41:32.470
Because that -- I do think, you
know, you could work harder.

00:41:32.470 --> 00:41:33.770
You can travel.

00:41:33.770 --> 00:41:35.070
Absolutely.

00:41:35.070 --> 00:41:39.160
But I do think those
relationships are your foundation.

00:41:39.160 --> 00:41:42.590
Right? When things go wrong,
that's what catches you.

00:41:42.590 --> 00:41:45.140
Whether it's your family,
or it's your best friends.

00:41:45.140 --> 00:41:47.480
And family is anything,
people you love.

00:41:47.480 --> 00:41:49.930
Whom you chose to make your family.

00:41:49.930 --> 00:41:51.950
So I do think that's important.

00:41:51.950 --> 00:41:55.640
I think it's -- I would say
it's a time when you can spend.

00:41:55.640 --> 00:41:58.540
More time on your work
than your relationships.

00:41:58.540 --> 00:42:03.080
But I would say you
shouldn't ever do only one.

00:42:03.080 --> 00:42:04.900
To the exclusion of the other.

00:42:04.900 --> 00:42:07.140
If you possibly can.

00:42:07.140 --> 00:42:08.760
&gt;&gt; Mary Louise Kelly:
But to the specific point

00:42:08.760 --> 00:42:10.580
about how important
it is in your 20s.

00:42:10.580 --> 00:42:12.370
You know, a year out of college.

00:42:12.370 --> 00:42:13.670
To ramp up --

00:42:13.670 --> 00:42:14.970
&gt;&gt; Anne-Marie Slaughter:
To go for it.

00:42:14.970 --> 00:42:16.270
&gt;&gt; Mary Louise Kelly: --
Fast, and just go for it.

00:42:16.270 --> 00:42:18.800
I mean, you do write about how much
easier it has made your choices

00:42:18.800 --> 00:42:20.100
and path.

00:42:20.100 --> 00:42:22.570
That you got to a pretty
successful point in your career.

00:42:22.570 --> 00:42:23.870
Relatively early on.

00:42:23.870 --> 00:42:25.170
So that you were the boss.

00:42:25.170 --> 00:42:27.540
And you could set the
agenda and the schedule.

00:42:27.540 --> 00:42:28.840
&gt;&gt; Anne-Marie Slaughter: I do.

00:42:28.840 --> 00:42:30.670
But I also -- I was divorced at 30.

00:42:30.670 --> 00:42:32.130
And married again at 35.

00:42:32.130 --> 00:42:33.800
And I got tenure in between.

00:42:33.800 --> 00:42:37.440
And I sometimes wonder, what
if I hadn't been divorced?

00:42:37.440 --> 00:42:40.190
What if we were having
children in our early 30s?

00:42:40.190 --> 00:42:42.580
And I've also written about my
infertility problems, right?

00:42:42.580 --> 00:42:44.870
I waited until I was 35.

00:42:44.870 --> 00:42:46.340
And I had a child at 38.

00:42:46.340 --> 00:42:48.410
And that was a terrible period.

00:42:48.410 --> 00:42:51.750
Where I really thought, I
have sacrificed my ability.

00:42:51.750 --> 00:42:54.500
To have biological
children, to my career.

00:42:54.500 --> 00:42:57.770
And so part of what I'm
saying now is, that's right.

00:42:57.770 --> 00:43:02.070
I mean, if you ask me -- if you
come to me as a young woman.

00:43:02.070 --> 00:43:04.050
Given the world we're in.

00:43:04.050 --> 00:43:07.940
I'm realistic enough to say,
hey, try to make partner first.

00:43:07.940 --> 00:43:10.720
Try to get to a place first.

00:43:10.720 --> 00:43:14.170
But I'll also say, try to
do that by your early 30s.

00:43:14.170 --> 00:43:16.150
Not your late 30s.

00:43:16.150 --> 00:43:20.120
But what I'm saying in this book
is, it doesn't have to be that way.

00:43:20.120 --> 00:43:24.770
Right? We should be able to
say, you've gotten up to here.

00:43:24.770 --> 00:43:26.430
On whatever path you're on.

00:43:26.430 --> 00:43:27.880
You now slow down.

00:43:27.880 --> 00:43:29.180
You don't drop out.

00:43:29.180 --> 00:43:30.480
You slow down.

00:43:30.480 --> 00:43:31.780
You have your children.

00:43:31.780 --> 00:43:33.080
You do whatever.

00:43:33.080 --> 00:43:34.380
And then, when you're ready.

00:43:34.380 --> 00:43:36.340
Your workplace ought to say, great.

00:43:36.340 --> 00:43:37.640
You're ready.

00:43:37.640 --> 00:43:38.940
Let's see if you can do the job.

00:43:38.940 --> 00:43:41.560
But yes, given where we are.

00:43:41.560 --> 00:43:46.380
It is a good idea to get as high
as you can, as early as you can.

00:43:46.380 --> 00:43:47.680
&gt;&gt; Mary Louise Kelly: All right.

00:43:47.680 --> 00:43:48.980
I'm going to take one last one.

00:43:48.980 --> 00:43:50.280
If you can keep it quick.

00:43:50.280 --> 00:43:51.580
Right here.

00:43:51.580 --> 00:43:52.880
&gt;&gt; Sure. You talked a little
bit about this in the talk.

00:43:52.880 --> 00:43:54.180
But I'd like to hear
a little bit more.

00:43:54.180 --> 00:43:56.620 position:56%
What effect do you believe a
continued prevalence and acceptance?

00:43:56.620 --> 00:43:59.760
Of children raised by
same-sex couples will have?

00:43:59.760 --> 00:44:03.480
On accelerating the decoupling
and dismantling of gender-biases.

00:44:03.480 --> 00:44:07.450
Related to how we align
caregiving in our careers?

00:44:07.450 --> 00:44:12.140
Both in terms of public
policy and corporate practice.

00:44:12.140 --> 00:44:13.980
&gt;&gt; Anne-Marie Slaughter: I'm so
glad you asked that question.

00:44:13.980 --> 00:44:17.260
I think same-sex couples
are leading the way.

00:44:17.260 --> 00:44:21.450
And indeed, it was early on, when
I was giving a talk on my article.

00:44:21.450 --> 00:44:24.370
When a young woman
came up to me and said.

00:44:24.370 --> 00:44:27.260
You know, I and my partner
-- it was another woman.

00:44:27.260 --> 00:44:30.380
She said, there is
no default role here.

00:44:30.380 --> 00:44:33.520
There is no, I'm the
woman, so I'm the caregiver.

00:44:33.520 --> 00:44:36.100
And she's the woman, so
she's the breadwinner.

00:44:36.100 --> 00:44:38.090
And ditto for two men.

00:44:38.090 --> 00:44:39.470
There is no default.

00:44:39.470 --> 00:44:43.970
And so what I argue, is we should
all think about it that way.

00:44:43.970 --> 00:44:47.530
It depends on your
personality, your ambitions.

00:44:47.530 --> 00:44:50.330
Your level of income, your boss.

00:44:50.330 --> 00:44:51.680
Where you are in life.

00:44:51.680 --> 00:44:54.400
All of those things
should determine.

00:44:54.400 --> 00:44:57.000
Who's lead parent and
who's lead breadwinner.

00:44:57.000 --> 00:45:00.210
And it doesn't always
have to be, you know,

00:45:00.210 --> 00:45:01.610
lead one and lead the other.

00:45:01.610 --> 00:45:04.080
There are times you can
really divide it equally.

00:45:04.080 --> 00:45:06.570
But those are the factors
that matter.

00:45:06.570 --> 00:45:11.690
Not whatever genitalia
you were born with.

00:45:11.690 --> 00:45:13.700
&gt;&gt; Mary Louise Kelly: I don't think
we can top that as an end place.

00:45:13.700 --> 00:45:15.000
So we will leave it there.

00:45:15.000 --> 00:45:16.610
Thank you, Anne-Marie
Slaughter, thank you.

00:45:16.610 --> 00:45:18.020
Thank you, everybody.

